    "words": "And for me, building off of that idea of having empathy and compassion for one another. Another, I think huge piece is having a safe space where people feel comfortable coming together because a huge piece is the having, for people to not feel isolated. So when there's some kind of community center where people can gather and meet at, that it goes a long way for people feeling connected to each other and that builds that piece on making that thriving and resilient community."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 25,
    "speaker_name": "Fiona",
    "words": "Yes."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 26,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "Now out of curiosity, that mention of community center, do you feel like that has to be something that is physical community center in a town? Or do you feel like that's something that's virtually accessible given the shift of everything over the last couple of years? I'm just always super curious what people have to say about that."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 27,
    "speaker_name": "Julianne",
    "words": "I mean, for me, what I was kind of thinking about Maine communities is that a lot of, especially in more rural areas, that community center might look like the local church or a synagogue that someone might go to. But from my experience it is virtual spaces because I do spend a lot more time in virtual community spaces. So I think you can vary person to person and area to area on what that looks like."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 28,
    "speaker_name": "Fiona",
    "words": "Yeah, that's great. I think that's another resource like you guys were talking about, having, sharing the resource of virtual spaces since often getting to a physical space isn't accessible when you live in a rural community or you aren't, you maybe immunocompromised, you don't want to be around other people. Yeah. Thank you guys so much for sharing those. So our next question is reflecting on your time working in youth mental health, what are the ways in which working in this industry has changed and how have you been expected to grow, learn, or change?"
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 29,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "I think one of the biggest pieces that I've seen as a shift has been away from the sad shock trauma approach to education and knowledge around mental health. For so long it was essentially scaring people out of suicidal thoughts and behaviors, scaring people out of being depressed and anxious. The wonderful advice that I think everyone is heard at some point, well have you tried just not worrying about it? Has always been the go-to fix for mental health. Whereas I feel like we've seen a time with a shift towards hope, health and strength, which has been something that's really important to our team in being able to have that shift in messaging because that's going to build that longer term resilience that's going to provide a whole lot more accessible messaging for our young people, honestly as well as adults because it's not othering the situation, it's instead inviting people in to have conversations around what's going well, how to grow, what's going well, and how it's okay for that to look different for every person."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 30,
    "speaker_name": "Libby",
    "words": "From doing youth mental health first aid trainings in particular, we meet a lot of community members, teachers, individuals in and around the school. And a concept that came up in our trainings is adults, staff, teachers are so scared to say the wrong thing, they're not saying anything at all. And that's not a blame by any means. I just thought that was really impactful to hear, because mental health, there is such a stigma around it still that it can be really scary to approach these conversations. If you notice warning signs in a young person and you want to help them and not knowing exactly what to say. And so I think for me personally, what I've learned, what I've grown with is you can literally say, \"Hey, I'm a support. I noticed some changes and I wanted to check in with you.\" I personally overcomplicate things and I'm not saying it's a simple topic by any means, but even though it's a scary conversation, being a support, being that trusted adult in someone's life is so much more important than saying the right thing. And so that was a really powerful thing for me to hear and to learn and kind of grow with. And working with young people directly. They want honest communication. I'm not saying treat them like adults because they're, they're young people, they're still learning, they're still growing, but being honest with them, \"Hey, even though I'm an adult, I don't have all of the answers, but I want to help you. I want to be there for you.\" So this was a big learning point for me and an adjustment in making sure that I am providing the best support for young people while letting them know that, hey, again, we're human at the end of the day and we're going to do the best that we can do."
  }
]

**Current turn**
{
