    "speaker_name": "Julianne",
    "words": "For me as a person who is newer in the youth mental health professional field, I think I've been working in a time that has been perpetuated by change with the pandemic, that we are just experiencing constant change in how the field operates, how we're dealing with mental health. And I think I've been seeing a lot of positive changes in the fact that we're having a lot more open conversations. People are recognizing that mental health is a significant issue, whereas when I was a youth, not too, too long ago that those conversations were not happening. They were not encouraged, they were, it was that fear tactic. Have you tried not worrying about it? Very dismissive. So I've been seeing those changes happening over the years. And in particular, I think the pandemic has been a bit of a speed run of that."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 32,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "I would definitely agree with that. Thinking about the growth learning and changing definitely around that flexibility and willingness to adapt to the needs in the moment. I can't think of how many times that we have met with schools with a plan going in for a couple hour session with them on something and those plans getting completely derailed because we need to talk about self care with the adults because they might be approaching burnout at such a high rate that if we don't slow down and have that conversation, they're not going to hear and absorb any of the other content and information that we're going to be sharing with them. We can provide all of the awesome knowledge, resource, skills, abilities to folks, but if they're not in a space to hear it, to be able to internalize and reflect on that themselves, then it's gone in one ear out the other. And so being able to adjust and go with the flow a whole lot more than I feel like in the past has been needed. In terms of growing, something that I encountered when learning more about pronoun usage in conversation and introductions ongoing, is this concept of messing up gracefully. And that has just really resonated with me in all of the ways. So definitely comes out of the conversations and learning around pronouns, but it's something that I feel is important that we take and apply to all areas of our lives. There's such this focus on, as adults, we've got to do things right the first time. We've got to be perfect, knock it out, not have any struggles or problems or difficulties to overcome or overcome something. And instead by having that willingness to try something, try something we might fail at, commit and move forward until we learn that, hey, that wasn't the right way. That wasn't the right thing. But being able to be humble and secure enough in ourselves to be able to acknowledge that, hey, I said the wrong thing there. I'd like to make it right by doing X, Y, Z, I'm sorry, moving on. Taking ownership when we misspeak, when we misstep, when we don't act, when we should have acted. Again, acknowledging the human component to each of us, but also taking that responsibility within ourselves to speak up and to shine a light on that, to really normalize that none of us are operating at a hundred percent, none of us are perfect walking around and that's okay."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 33,
    "speaker_name": "Fiona",
    "words": "Yeah. Is that something that when you're going to schools and meeting with teachers that you're sharing that important piece with, because they are working with young students and as a teacher, I'm sure as what you were saying, they're afraid to say the wrong thing. Is that something that comes up?"
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 34,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "Absolutely. We spend a lot of time talking point blank about the necessity of we need to break down these walls that we have spent so many years building up, obviously always maintaining appropriate boundaries and professionalism. Of course, however, we need to stop projecting this image to our young people that some magical thing happens on your 18th birthday where you get imparted with all of the knowledge that you could ever possibly need. Because I don't know about you, hasn't happened for me just yet, maybe any day. But by showing that as adults, that we make mistakes that we're still learning, that we, are we sure of the next step, that can really build confidence for a young person because they don't feel like there's something wrong with them. They don't feel like they're not doing enough or knowing enough or good enough. Instead, they see that, that's a really normal part of life and that, that's worth talking about. It's not something you have to hide or be ashamed of."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 35,
    "speaker_name": "Fiona",
    "words": "Yeah. Yeah."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 36,
    "speaker_name": "Libby",
    "words": "And we're hoping that that piece will also be a support for adults as well, that they don't have to hold this, I'm perfect all of the time. And by no means are we saying that you should not be paying attention to warning signs and doing all of those things. We're saying, yes, do your job, do those things, but no one's perfect."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 37,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "And that's another piece of why we encourage as many people as we can to engage in education around youth mental health. Because when we accept that I am not perfect as an individual, but hey, if I have all of the people around me are also keeping an eye, if they are also putting their knowledge and cognizance out there in the world that between the team of us, we're going to see a whole lot more. We're going to be able to be a better resource together than as one person that's trying to hold it together as the go-to for all in everything. Really encouraging that team approach, collectivism more so in the response to supporting our young people."
  }
]

