  {
    "speaker_turn": 50,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "Yes. I think that people as a whole definitely value that. I think that being the individual working in the field, it can feel like systemically that you are not valued. And I think that's where the notion of boundaries and self care come into practice so much or the necessity of that because the work that people are doing, whether it be on a systems level, on a direct service level, what you're doing matters. And the people that you are engaging with see that and know that and connect with that, even though the amount of paperwork probably grows on a weekly basis, the insurance reimbursement things are not going to treat you like you matter. The news is probably not going to treat you like you matter. All of these big pieces that we see floating around, having opinions on things don't necessarily show that care and support, but the individuals, the actual community being served absolutely, completely valued, appreciated, and should be openly celebrated."
