  {
    "speaker_turn": 51,
    "speaker_name": "Fiona",
    "words": "We got a thumbs up from Libby. Our next question. Oh, okay. Yeah, plenty of time. What ideas do you have for youth mental health organizations in schools and other learning environments? Let me rephrase that. What ideas do you have for how youth mental health organizations can work more fruitfully together with schools and other learning environments?"
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 52,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "More. More agencies, more providers, more resources to be able to offer to the schools. But these schools need more time, more funding, more teachers, more paraprofessionals, and it feels like both systems are in crisis mode in their own right. And trying to get that collaboration and prevention work going together when people are just trying to get through the day to make it through makes that really difficult. And so I think that when we have administrations in school and when we have teachers and professionals and other staff that are at schools that are wanting to not just get through but feel interested in learning more, when they feel supported in learning more. So when the messaging is coming down from them or from their powers that be, that it is a strength to learn more, to be an updated kind of support for the young people, not just the messaging of get through the day, we'll make it to tomorrow. That can make a huge difference in the partnerships."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 53,
    "speaker_name": "Libby",
    "words": "We have a wonderful upstream suicide prevention program that we're working to get into as many Maine schools as possible. Right now it's really strength based and looking to the strengths that you have available to you to help work through life ups and downs, everyday stressors that are showing up for you. And we've found that schools are really excited about this program and want to be super invested. However, the lack of subs, the lack of time to be able to be away from the classroom, to be trained in this program and feeling like one more thing added to their plate has really made them hesitant to bring the program to schools. And so as Kristel said, I think more was a great way to sum that up. More time, more subs, more resources, more support so that they are able to connect and have these programs that they want to have, but the access accessibility is not right there for them to be able to get these programs going."
