    "words": "We need to be able to have the space and room to be able to help our young people as whole people, not as checklists, not as standards meeting, not as whatever other procedure might be in place. We need to be able to give our parents, caregivers, teachers, paraprofessionals, every other individual that is connecting with our young people to give them as much of the tools and resources and time in space to help our young people. To stop putting this culture of busy on everyone. To be able to slow things down some so that an individual can be seen as a whole person, not just a student that happens to be in a math class today, or a difficult teenager that works in the grocery store that's bothering you that day, but rather as whole people with whole lives and experiences that are going to need different supports in different ways at different times."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 67,
    "speaker_name": "Libby",
    "words": "And that we're partners in this. We all want the best for the young people in Maine. And part of that is, as I mentioned earlier, all of us being a piece of the puzzle that helps support them. We want young people to know that if you're struggling with your mental health, there are resources out there. There are things you can look to. And so we want to partner with all schools and be there to help support them and the young people. So just thinking of us as partners to support young people is really important."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 68,
    "speaker_name": "Julianne",
    "words": "And I would agree completely with both Kristel and Libby on that. And I think I would add, just listen to the youth. If there's something going on in the school culturally or there's a policy and students are saying they don't like it or they'd love to see a change, they want to add something into the school, some kind of program to make things better, listen to them and talk with them. Meet them on their level and have a conversation. See what you can do to help them make it happen or tell them in a way that makes sense to them, why it might not be able to. Just respect them, respect them as people, and not look at them as children because they are more capable than sometimes they're given credit for."
  },
  {
    "speaker_turn": 69,
    "speaker_name": "Kristel",
    "words": "Absolutely. As a quick add-on to that, I think of recently, Libby and I met with a group of students that were expressing some frustrations with the culture at their school that there was a culture of physical violence at this school and they were worried about how the school was responding or not responding. And they took it upon themself to put together these flyers, posters that they wanted to put up around the school to encourage communication. And it was done in such a respectful manner. It was very accessible in the way that they were designed. It was wonderful to see a young person take it upon themselves to do something like that, to essentially make an action plan and want to follow through on it. The difficulty that we saw in that moment was this young person came to the school so excited to be able to hopefully do something about this problem that they're seeing. And instead of being met with excitement or, Wow, great job with that. Let's see how to integrate that. It almost felt dismissive. And that's where a lot of our problems are stemming out of. We have adults that are working with young people that got into it for all of the right reasons, and their heart has been there through everything, but they have been stretched so thin, and they have had to give everything and have more asked of them on an ongoing basis that they don't always have enough left in them to be able to make that connection, to be able to be that resource and support. So we need to build out these systems in a meaningful way that makes it sustainable, that makes it so these people that care and want to help our young people can do that work. And that is a huge shift that we need to make."
